CM 3015 Machine Learning and Neural Networks Final Project - Vehicle Identification with CIFAR-10¶

William Liem¶

I. Introduction¶

In today's everchanging society, the advancement of technology is growing very fast. Smart devices are now available in many forms such as phones, tablets, and vehicles. The problem we will be discussing today is correlated to smart vehicles. In theory, smart vehicles should be able to drive themselves without human assistance. But as of now in 2024, it is not fully a reality yet.

One of the main problems of automated smart vehicles is safety. The vehicle should be able to drive as if a human is driving. So, it should be able to identify other vehicles on the road to prevent accidents. In this project, I aim to train a machine how to do vehicle identification with the CIFAR-10 dataset.

The CIFAR-10 dataset includes 10 classes (airplane, automobile, bird, cat, deer, dog, frog, horse, ship, truck) and 60.000 images. It contains 6000 images per class with a size of 32x32. For this project, we are just going to focus on 4 vehicle classes which are airplanes, automobiles, ships, and trucks. In total, 24.000 images will be used for this project. Not all of these vehicles are meant to be driven on the road but it is a good starting point.

I am going to conduct this project based on the Universal Flow of Machine Learning of DLWP 4.5 (1st edition) (https://bookdown.org/paul/2021_computational_social_science/the-universal-workflow-of-machine-learning.html).

Methodology of Training and Testing¶

The steps that will be taken for this experiment include:

  1. Import necessary modules and dataset to the project. For this project, it is the CIFAR-10 dataset.
  2. Pre-process data in order to be suitable for the models (Normalization, One-hot encoding, and Data augmentation).
  3. Complete Naive Bayes baseline test to acquire baseline accuracy. The result will be the minimum target requirement.
  4. Design 2 models, a simple one and an overfit one.
  5. Train the models with the dataset, while experimenting with parameters (epochs, batch size, learning rate).
  6. Test and evaluate the models, visualize the results, and do validation test with external data.
  7. Create a new model, adding optimization to the overfit model to get rid of the overfitting (on the assumption that it performs better than the simple model).
  8. Repeat step 5 and 6.

Aims and Objectives¶

The metrics to measure the success of the project include:

  • Accuracy (Naive baseline or above):
    • Training Accuracy (train data + data augmentation)
    • Validation Accuracy (val data + data augmentation)
    • Evaluation Score accuracy (test data (pure))
  • Minimize overfitting and noise (jagged lines) as much as possible.
  • Observe the loss graph and make sure it goes down.

The aims and objectives of this project include:

  1. Importing and understanding the CIFAR-10 dataset to use for building a neural network.
  2. Develop 2 models, 1 simple and 1 deep model, using only Sequential, Dense, and Dropout layers.
  3. Train, test, and validate models.
  4. Optimize overfit model, as a separate model.
  5. By the end of the experiment, the models should surpass Naive baseline accuracy (without CNN).
  6. Conclude factors to making an optimal model.

# Load CIFAR-10 dataset
(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test) = cifar10.load_data()

# Define the classes you want to keep (e.g., airplane, automobile, ship, truck)
vehicle_index = [0, 1, 8, 9]  # indices of airplane, automobile, ship, truck

# Filter the training set
train_mask = np.isin(y_train, vehicle_index)
X_train = X_train[train_mask[:, 0]]
y_train = y_train[train_mask[:, 0]]

# Filter the test set
test_mask = np.isin(y_test, vehicle_index)
X_test = X_test[test_mask[:, 0]]
y_test = y_test[test_mask[:, 0]]

# Split the training set into training and validation sets
X_train, X_valid, y_train, y_valid = train_test_split(
    X_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

II. Data Pre-processing¶

Before training the model, we have to pre-process and prepare the data in order for it to be suitable for the model. Some of the pre-processing done include:¶

  • Do normalization. Turn X data into floats between 0-1.
  • Do one-hot encoding. Turn y data (target) into categorical data.
  • Perform data augmentation to 'simulate' a more variative training data. Since I have cut down the training data by a significant amount, it is wise to do this in order to simulate a larger dataset.

III. Determining baseline accuracy using Naive Baseline Accuracy¶

Before making the Neural networks, I need to determine the baseline target for the experiment with Naive Baseline. Nave Bayes assumes a generative model for each class. Then, these generative models predict labels for new points. It is a good starting point/baseline for classification tasks.

In [8]:
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Create a Gaussian Naive Bayes classifier
clf = GaussianNB()

# turn into 1d array for this baseline
X_train_baseline = X_train.reshape(X_train.shape[0], -1)
X_test_baseline = X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0], -1)

y_train_baseline = y_train.argmax(axis=1)
y_test_baseline = y_test.argmax(axis=1)

# train the classifier on flattened training data
clf.fit(X_train_baseline, y_train_baseline)

# make predictions on flattened test data 
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test_baseline)

# calculate the accuracy of the predictions (baseline score)
baseline_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_baseline, y_pred)

print("The baseline accuracy for this project is: {:.2f}%".format(baseline_accuracy * 100))

The baseline accuracy for this project is: 50.12%

The percentage above must be achieved by the models and a higher accuracy is favorable.

Additionally, a study from Montreal University Canada was conducted in 2016, training models with the CIFAR-10 dataset without any CNN layers. The results of the study were that an accuracy of 55% - 70% can be achieved depending on various parameters and tuning. But, an accuracy of 90% is simply impossible without ConvNet layers. So I may aim for 60%+ accuracy for this project.

IV. Training, Testing, and Evaluating Models¶

I will be developing 3 models, a simple, overfit, and most optimal model based on the results of the previous 2 models. The metric to grade the models will be accuracy. A history graph will be observed to determine overfitting. Additionally, a testing/validation process is done with some external images outside the database to see how the models will fair against the foreign data.

The layers will have relu activation, the last layer will be soft max, and categorical_crossentropy will be used for the loss function. categorical_crossentropy is used because the dataset is multi-class, but single-label.

Adam will be used for the optimizer.

These metrics will be used for all models to achieve consistent results across the board.

A. Simple shallow model¶

  • has flatten layer to convert array to 1D.
  • has 2 Dense layers, to apply relu and softmax.
  • Practically only 1 layer does the filtering.
  • Results will most likely be overfit

In [14]:
# function to validate model against random images
def validate_model(urls, model, class_names):
    for url in urls:
        resp = urllib.request.urlopen(url)
        image = np.asarray(bytearray(resp.read()), dtype="uint8")
        image = cv2.imdecode(image, cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED)

        # Convert the image from BGR to RGB
        image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

        # Resize it to 32x32 pixels
        image = cv2.resize(image, (32,32))

        # Normalize the image
        image = image/255

        # Add an extra dimension because the model expects a batch of images
        image = image.reshape((1, 32, 32, 3))

        # Predict the class
        prediction = model.predict(image)
        predicted_class = prediction.argmax()

        # Display the image as well
        plt.imshow(image.reshape(32, 32, 3))
        plt.title(f'Predicted class: {class_names[predicted_class]}')
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.show()

# from tensorflow.keras import layers, models, regularizers

optimized_model = Sequential([
                    Flatten(input_shape=(32, 32, 3)),
                    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
                    Dense(64, activation='relu'), 
                    Dropout(0.1),
                    Dense(32, activation='relu'),  
                    Dense(16, activation='relu'),
                    Dense(10, activation='softmax'),    
], name='optimized_model')

Compiling and training the model.¶

The batch_size, epochs, and learning_rate are customizable so I can play with them during development. A validation dataset is also available. This allows the model to test itself on unseen data on every epoch/step of training.

The parameters have been upgraded from the previous training to improve results even further.

V. RESULTS AND CONCLUSION¶

Evaluation Results:

  • Simple: 62.2%
  • Overfit: 67.2%
  • Optimized: 66.7%

After countless trial and errors, I completed the experiment where all the models surpass the naive baseline accuracy (50.12%). They all surpassed the baseline target by more than 10%.

The results from this experiment suggests that the overfit model is the most consistently accurate model. The optimized model has a dropout layer in between the Dense layers and was trained differently, resulting in less overfitting but sacrificing a little bit of accuracy in the process. The optimization done seemed to have helped in reducing noise (jagged lines) in the graph.

It is important to remember that the CIFAR-10 is a complex dataset and using only Sequential, Dense, and Dropout layers does not do the dataset justice when creating a model. CNN is needed for an exceptionally accurate model.

In conclusion, adding many layers to train a complex dataset such as the CIFAR-10 is the solution to achieving better results. Optimizing it with dropout layers is advisable to reduce noise and overfitting as well as optimizing the training process. However, this process will most likely reduce a bit of accuracy in the process, and making the choice of optimization dependent on the user's needs.
